  "prompt": "What were the terms to the Treaty of Versailles?",
  "response": "The **Treaty of Versailles** was the peace treaty signed on **June 28, 1919**, that officially ended **World War I** between the Allied Powers and Germany. The treaty aimed to punish Germany and establish a new international order. Its key terms included:\n\n### 1. **Territorial Losses**\n   - Germany lost significant territory, including:\n     - **Alsace-Lorraine** to France.\n     - **Eupen-Malm\u00e9dy** to Belgium.\n     - **Northern Schleswig** to Denmark.\n     - **Posen**, **West Prussia**, and parts of **Upper Silesia** to Poland (creating the \"Polish Corridor\").\n     - **Danzig** (Gda\u0144sk) became a **free city** under League of Nations control.\n     - Territories in the **Saar Basin** placed under League of Nations control for 15 years, with France given coal-mining rights.\n     - All **overseas colonies** (e.g., in Africa and the Pacific) were redistributed as mandates under the League of Nations.\n\n### 2. **Military Restrictions**\n   - Germany\u2019s military was severely limited:\n     - Army reduced to **100,000 troops**.\n     - Prohibited from having an **air force**.\n     - Navy limited to **6 battleships**, with no submarines allowed.\n     - **Rhineland** was demilitarized.\n\n### 3. **War Guilt and Reparations**\n   - **Article 231** (the \"War Guilt Clause\") held Germany solely responsible for the war.\n   - Germany was required to pay **reparations** for damages caused by the war. The exact amount was later set at **132 billion gold marks** (approximately $33 billion at the time), a sum that was economically crippling.\n\n### 4. **League of Nations**\n   - The Treaty established the **League of Nations**, an international organization aimed at maintaining peace. However, Germany was initially excluded from joining.\n\n### 5. **Other Provisions**\n   - Prohibition of the **Anschluss** (union) between Germany and Austria.\n   - Germany was required to recognize the independence of **new nations** like Poland, Czechoslovakia, and the Baltic states.\n   - Restrictions on Germany\u2019s ability to produce or trade in military equipment.\n\n### Impact of the Treaty\nThe Treaty of Versailles was highly controversial and had significant consequences:\n   - It sowed resentment in Germany, contributing to the rise of **Adolf Hitler** and the **Nazi Party**.\n   - The reparations and economic restrictions led to severe economic hardship in Germany, culminating in hyperinflation and social unrest.\n   - The treaty\u2019s harsh terms are often seen as a factor that led to **World War II**.\n\nThe Treaty of Versailles remains one of the most debated and consequential peace agreements in modern history.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
